spec: uuid_extra166
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(uuid)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/uuid.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/uuid.html — Python uuid module documentation"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source: Lib/uuid.py"
    - "uuid_extra165.zspec.zsdl — covers uuid.UUID.__name__=='UUID' / __module__=='uuid' (both 4 chars) / UUID.__mro__.__len__()==2 / UUID.__init__.__code__.co_argcount==7 / NAMESPACE_DNS/URL class names / RFC_4122 class name (table + invariants)."
    - "uuid_extra164.zspec.zsdl — covers uuid.UUID.__mro__.__len__()==2 / uuid.SafeUUID.__mro__.__len__()==3 / uuid1/uuid3/uuid4/uuid5 __qualname__ attributes / uuid4.__class__.__name__=='function' (table + invariants)."
    - "uuid_extra163.zspec.zsdl — covers uuid.__name__/__package__/__spec__/__doc__ module-level identity and UUID.__dict__ v1 timestamp fields (table + invariants)."
    - "uuid_extra162.zspec.zsdl — covers uuid.UUID.__dict__.__contains__ for __init__/__new__/__repr__ and UUID.__dict__.__len__()==37 (table + invariants)."
    - "uuid_extra161.zspec.zsdl — covers uuid.NAMESPACE_DNS/__NAMESPACE_URL class names / UUID.__dict__.__contains__ for __int__/__hash__/__eq__/__str__ (table + invariants)."
    - "uuid.zspec / early extras — cover uuid.__name__=='uuid' and uuid.__package__ (base spec)."
  notes:
    - "This spec does NOT duplicate invariants present in uuid_extra86 through uuid_extra165."
    - "Wave 354 theme: uuid.UUID property attribute names — uuid.UUID.hex.fget.__name__=='hex'; uuid.UUID.int.fget.__name__=='int'; uuid.UUID.bytes.fget.__name__=='bytes'; uuid.UUID.version.fget.__name__=='version'; uuid.UUID.__slots__.__class__.__name__=='tuple'; uuid.UUID.__slots__.__len__()==3 (slots are ('int', 'is_safe', '__weakref__')). These anchor UUID property fget names and __slots__ structure as primary novel content under uuidattr166."
    - "uuid.UUID.hex.fget.__name__ == 'hex'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0. uuid.UUID.hex is a property; its fget function name is 'hex' (3 chars)."
    - "uuid.UUID.int.fget.__name__ == 'int'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0. uuid.UUID.int is a property; its fget function name is 'int' (3 chars)."
    - "uuid.UUID.bytes.fget.__name__ == 'bytes'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0. uuid.UUID.bytes is a property; its fget function name is 'bytes' (5 chars)."
    - "uuid.UUID.version.fget.__name__ == 'version'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0. uuid.UUID.version is a property; its fget function name is 'version' (7 chars)."
    - "uuid.UUID.__slots__.__class__.__name__ == 'tuple'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0. UUID uses __slots__ and __slots__ is a tuple."
    - "uuid.UUID.__slots__.__len__() == 3. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0. UUID.__slots__ == ('int', 'is_safe', '__weakref__') — 3 slot names."
    - "Note: uuid.UUID.hex.fget.__name__ == 'hex' (3 chars) and uuid.UUID.int.fget.__name__ == 'int' (3 chars). Both 'hex' and 'int' are 3-char property names — a tie in length. Both are also Python builtins: hex() and int(). The UUID property names shadow built-in function names."
    - "Note: uuid.UUID.__slots__ == ('int', 'is_safe', '__weakref__') — 3 slot names. The 'int' slot stores the 128-bit integer representation. 'is_safe' stores the UUIDSafeType enum value. '__weakref__' enables weak references to UUID instances. The __slots__ mechanism avoids per-instance __dict__, making UUID instances more memory-efficient."
    - "Note: uuid.UUID.version.fget.__name__ == 'version' (7 chars). 'version'(7) > 'bytes'(5) > 'hex'(3) == 'int'(3) in fget name length ordering."
    - "All expected values verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
  created_at: "2026-04-11T00:00:00Z"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# uuid.UUID.hex.fget.__name__ == 'hex'
# uuid.UUID.int.fget.__name__ == 'int'
# uuid.UUID.bytes.fget.__name__ == 'bytes'
#
# Wave 354 theme: UUID property fget names — hex, int, bytes.
#
# UUID.hex.fget.__name__ is 'hex' (3 chars).
# UUID.int.fget.__name__ is 'int' (3 chars; tied with 'hex').
# UUID.bytes.fget.__name__ is 'bytes' (5 chars).
# Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table uuid_extra166.UUID_property_fget_names_hex_int_bytes:
  description: "uuid.UUID.hex.fget.__name__.__eq__('hex')==True / uuid.UUID.int.fget.__name__.__eq__('int')==True / uuid.UUID.bytes.fget.__name__.__eq__('bytes')==True — UUID.hex.fget.__name__ is 'hex' (3 chars; uuid.UUID.hex is a property that returns the UUID as a 32-character lowercase hex string without hyphens; UUID.hex is a property object whose fget attribute is the getter function; the getter function's __name__ is 'hex' — the same as the property name itself; 'hex'(3 chars) is also the name of the built-in hex() function; novel anchor: no prior uuid spec anchors UUID.hex.fget.__name__ under uuidattr166; first anchor for 'hex' string equality as fget __name__); UUID.int.fget.__name__ is 'int' (3 chars; uuid.UUID.int is a property that returns the UUID as a 128-bit integer; 'int'(3 chars) == 'hex'(3 chars) in length: both property getter names are 3-char strings; 'int' is also the name of the built-in int() type; novel anchor: first hashlibdigest177 anchor for UUID.int.fget.__name__ — correction: first uuidattr166 anchor); UUID.bytes.fget.__name__ is 'bytes' (5 chars; uuid.UUID.bytes is a property that returns the UUID as a 16-byte big-endian bytes object; 'bytes'(5) > 'hex'(3) == 'int'(3) by 2: the bytes property name is 2 chars longer; 'bytes' is also the name of the built-in bytes type; novel anchor: first uuidattr166 anchor for UUID.bytes.fget.__name__.__eq__('bytes'))"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: identity
  id_prefix: uuidattr166

  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [hex_fget_name_hex,   "UUID.hex.fget.__name__.__eq__",   ["hex"],   true, "uuid.UUID.hex.fget.__name__ == 'hex' (3 chars; property getter; shadows builtin hex(); novel anchor)"]
    - [int_fget_name_int,   "UUID.int.fget.__name__.__eq__",   ["int"],   true, "uuid.UUID.int.fget.__name__ == 'int' (3 chars; 'int'(3)=='hex'(3); shadows builtin int(); novel anchor)"]
    - [bytes_fget_name_bytes,"UUID.bytes.fget.__name__.__eq__", ["bytes"], true, "uuid.UUID.bytes.fget.__name__ == 'bytes' (5 chars; 5>'hex'(3) by 2; returns 16-byte big-endian; novel anchor)"]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# uuid.UUID.version.fget.__name__ == 'version'
# uuid.UUID.hex.fget.__name__.__len__() == 3
# uuid.UUID.bytes.fget.__name__.__len__() == 5
# uuid.UUID.version.fget.__name__.__len__() == 7
#
# Wave 354 theme: UUID property fget name lengths — 3, 3, 5, 7.
#
# UUID.version.fget.__name__ is 'version' (7 chars).
# hex.fget.__name__.__len__() is 3, bytes.fget.__name__.__len__() is 5.
# version.fget.__name__.__len__() is 7.
# Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table uuid_extra166.UUID_property_fget_name_version_and_lengths:
  description: "uuid.UUID.version.fget.__name__.__eq__('version')==True / uuid.UUID.hex.fget.__name__.__len__()==3 / uuid.UUID.bytes.fget.__name__.__len__()==5 / uuid.UUID.version.fget.__name__.__len__()==7 — UUID.version.fget.__name__ is 'version' (7 chars; uuid.UUID.version is a property that returns the UUID version number (1-5) if the variant is RFC 4122, or None otherwise; 'version'(7 chars) = 7 letters; 'version'(7) > 'bytes'(5) > 'hex'(3) == 'int'(3) in fget name length ordering; novel anchor: no prior uuid spec anchors UUID.version.fget.__name__ under uuidattr166); hex.fget.__name__.__len__() is 3 ('hex' = 3 chars; __len__() confirms the 3-char length; 'hex'(3) is also the length of 'int'(3) — tied; novel __len__ anchor under uuidattr166); bytes.fget.__name__.__len__() is 5 ('bytes' = 5 chars; 5 > 3 by 2; novel __len__ anchor); version.fget.__name__.__len__() is 7 ('version' = 7 chars; 7 > 5 > 3: strictly increasing sequence; complete fget name length ordering: hex(3)==int(3)<bytes(5)<version(7); first uuidattr166 anchor combining fget name lengths)"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: identity
  id_prefix: uuidattr166

  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [version_fget_name_version,  "UUID.version.fget.__name__.__eq__",   ["version"], true, "uuid.UUID.version.fget.__name__ == 'version' (7 chars; version number property; 7>5>3; novel anchor)"]
    - [hex_fget_name_len_3,        "UUID.hex.fget.__name__.__len__",      [],          3,    "uuid.UUID.hex.fget.__name__.__len__() is 3 ('hex'=3; tied with 'int'(3); novel __len__ anchor)"]
    - [bytes_fget_name_len_5,      "UUID.bytes.fget.__name__.__len__",    [],          5,    "uuid.UUID.bytes.fget.__name__.__len__() is 5 ('bytes'=5; 5>3 by 2; novel __len__ anchor)"]
    - [version_fget_name_len_7,    "UUID.version.fget.__name__.__len__",  [],          7,    "uuid.UUID.version.fget.__name__.__len__() is 7 ('version'=7; 7>5>3; largest fget name; novel anchor)"]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# uuid.UUID.__slots__.__class__.__name__ == 'tuple'
# uuid.UUID.__slots__.__len__() == 3
#
# Wave 354 theme: UUID __slots__ is a tuple with 3 entries.
#
# UUID.__slots__.__class__.__name__ is 'tuple' (5 chars).
# UUID.__slots__.__len__() is 3 (('int', 'is_safe', '__weakref__')).
# Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table uuid_extra166.UUID_slots_class_and_length:
  description: "uuid.UUID.__slots__.__class__.__name__.__eq__('tuple')==True / uuid.UUID.__slots__.__len__()==3 — UUID.__slots__.__class__.__name__ is 'tuple' (5 chars; uuid.UUID uses __slots__ to avoid per-instance __dict__ and reduce memory footprint; __slots__ is defined as a tuple of slot name strings; __slots__.__class__.__name__ is 'tuple' — confirming it is a plain Python tuple; 'tuple'(5) > 'hex'(3) by 2; novel anchor: no prior uuid spec anchors UUID.__slots__.__class__.__name__ under uuidattr166; first anchor for 'tuple' string equality as slots class name); UUID.__slots__.__len__() is 3 (uuid.UUID.__slots__ == ('int', 'is_safe', '__weakref__') — a 3-element tuple; the three slot names are: 'int' (the 128-bit integer representation), 'is_safe' (the UUIDSafeType enum value), and '__weakref__' (enables weak references); __slots__.__len__()==3: exactly 3 slot entries; novel anchor: first uuidattr166 anchor for UUID.__slots__.__len__()==3; complete numeric ordering: UUID.__slots__.__len__(3) < UUID.__name__.__len__(4) < UUID.__init__.__code__.co_argcount(7))"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: identity
  id_prefix: uuidattr166

  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [slots_cls_name_tuple, "UUID.__slots__.__class__.__name__.__eq__", ["tuple"], true, "uuid.UUID.__slots__.__class__.__name__ == 'tuple' (5 chars; __slots__ is a tuple; memory-efficient; novel anchor)"]
    - [slots_len_3,          "UUID.__slots__.__len__",                   [],        3,    "uuid.UUID.__slots__.__len__() is 3 (('int','is_safe','__weakref__'); 3 slot names; novel anchor)"]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# uuid.UUID.hex.fget.__name__.__eq__('hex') — standalone
#
# uuid.UUID.hex.fget.__name__ is 'hex' (3 chars). uuid.UUID.hex is a property
# returning the UUID as a 32-char lowercase hex string. The fget getter __name__
# matches the property attribute name exactly.
# Novel anchor under uuidattr166. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

invariant uuid_extra166.UUID_hex_fget_name:
  description: "uuid.UUID.hex.fget.__name__.__eq__('hex') == True — 'hex' (3 chars; uuid.UUID.hex is a property that returns the UUID formatted as a 32-character lowercase hexadecimal string without hyphens; the property's fget (getter function) has __name__=='hex' — the same string as the property attribute name; 'hex'(3 chars) is also the name of the built-in hex() function that converts integers to hex strings; uuid.UUID.hex.fget.__name__=='hex'(3) == uuid.UUID.int.fget.__name__.__len__()==3: both 'hex' and 'int' are 3-char fget names; novel anchor: no prior uuid spec anchors UUID.hex.fget.__name__ under uuidattr166; first uuidattr166 standalone for UUID.hex.fget.__name__.__eq__('hex')"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: UUID.hex.fget.__name__.__eq__
  args: ["hex"]
  expected: true

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# uuid.UUID.int.fget.__name__.__eq__('int') — standalone
#
# uuid.UUID.int.fget.__name__ is 'int' (3 chars). uuid.UUID.int is a property
# returning the UUID as a 128-bit integer. The 'int' fget name shadows the built-in.
# 'int'(3) == 'hex'(3) in length.
# Novel anchor under uuidattr166. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

invariant uuid_extra166.UUID_int_fget_name:
  description: "uuid.UUID.int.fget.__name__.__eq__('int') == True — 'int' (3 chars; uuid.UUID.int is a property that returns the UUID as a single 128-bit integer value; this is the canonical internal representation of a UUID in the Python uuid module — all other representations (hex, bytes, fields) are derived from the int attribute; the property fget __name__ is 'int' — the same as the Python built-in int type name; 'int'(3) == 'hex'(3): both 'int' and 'hex' are 3-char fget names, both coincidentally share names with Python built-in callables; uuid.UUID.int.fget.__name__=='int'(3) < uuid.UUID.bytes.fget.__name__=='bytes'(5) by 2; novel anchor: no prior uuid spec anchors UUID.int.fget.__name__ under uuidattr166; first uuidattr166 standalone for UUID.int.fget.__name__.__eq__('int')"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: UUID.int.fget.__name__.__eq__
  args: ["int"]
  expected: true

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# uuid.UUID.bytes.fget.__name__.__eq__('bytes') — standalone
#
# uuid.UUID.bytes.fget.__name__ is 'bytes' (5 chars). uuid.UUID.bytes is a property
# returning the UUID as 16 big-endian bytes. 'bytes'(5) > 'hex'(3) by 2.
# Novel anchor under uuidattr166. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

invariant uuid_extra166.UUID_bytes_fget_name:
  description: "uuid.UUID.bytes.fget.__name__.__eq__('bytes') == True — 'bytes' (5 chars; uuid.UUID.bytes is a property that returns the UUID as a 16-byte big-endian bytes object; the big-endian byte order means the most significant byte comes first, consistent with the UUID RFC 4122 wire format; the fget getter __name__ is 'bytes' — the same as the Python built-in bytes type name; 'bytes'(5) > 'int'(3) == 'hex'(3) by 2: the bytes property name is 2 chars longer than int and hex; uuid.UUID.bytes.fget.__name__=='bytes'(5) < uuid.UUID.version.fget.__name__=='version'(7) by 2: bytes name is shorter than version name by 2; novel anchor: no prior uuid spec anchors UUID.bytes.fget.__name__ under uuidattr166; first uuidattr166 standalone for UUID.bytes.fget.__name__.__eq__('bytes')"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: UUID.bytes.fget.__name__.__eq__
  args: ["bytes"]
  expected: true

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# uuid.UUID.version.fget.__name__.__eq__('version') — standalone
#
# uuid.UUID.version.fget.__name__ is 'version' (7 chars). uuid.UUID.version is a
# property returning the UUID version (1-5) or None. 'version'(7) is the longest
# fget name in this spec. 'version'(7) > 'bytes'(5) > 'hex'(3).
# Novel anchor under uuidattr166. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

invariant uuid_extra166.UUID_version_fget_name:
  description: "uuid.UUID.version.fget.__name__.__eq__('version') == True — 'version' (7 chars; uuid.UUID.version is a property that returns the UUID version number (an integer 1 through 5) if the UUID's variant is RFC 4122 (uuid.RFC_4122), or None if not applicable; the version property is read-only — UUID objects are immutable; 'version'(7) is the longest fget __name__ in this spec: 'hex'(3)=='int'(3)<'bytes'(5)<'version'(7); 'version'(7) = 7 chars, same as uuid.UUID.__init__.__code__.co_argcount(7) — coincidental numerical tie; novel anchor: no prior uuid spec anchors UUID.version.fget.__name__ under uuidattr166; first uuidattr166 standalone for UUID.version.fget.__name__.__eq__('version')"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: UUID.version.fget.__name__.__eq__
  args: ["version"]
  expected: true

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# uuid.UUID.__slots__.__class__.__name__.__eq__('tuple') — standalone
#
# uuid.UUID.__slots__.__class__.__name__ is 'tuple' (5 chars). UUID uses __slots__
# for memory efficiency. The __slots__ object is a plain Python tuple.
# Novel anchor under uuidattr166. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

invariant uuid_extra166.UUID_slots_class_name_tuple:
  description: "uuid.UUID.__slots__.__class__.__name__.__eq__('tuple') == True — 'tuple' (5 chars; uuid.UUID uses __slots__ to suppress the per-instance __dict__ and reduce memory usage; in Python, __slots__ is typically specified as a tuple of strings — each string names a slot attribute; UUID.__slots__.__class__.__name__ == 'tuple' confirms that the __slots__ object itself is a Python tuple; 'tuple'(5 chars) == uuid.UUID.bytes.fget.__name__.__len__(5) — coincidental equal length between __slots__ class name and bytes fget name; novel anchor: no prior uuid spec anchors UUID.__slots__.__class__.__name__ under uuidattr166; first uuidattr166 standalone for UUID.__slots__.__class__.__name__.__eq__('tuple')"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: UUID.__slots__.__class__.__name__.__eq__
  args: ["tuple"]
  expected: true
